The given matrix corresponds to a projection. A projection matrix satisfies the property $P^2 = P$, where $P$ is the projection matrix. Let's denote the projection matrix as $P$:
\[P = \begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34} \\ c & \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix}\]

We need to find the values of $a$ and $c$ such that $P^2 = P$.
\begin{align*}
P^2 &= P \\
\begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34} \\ c & \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34} \\ c & \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34} \\ c & \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

Multiplying the matrices, we get:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} a^2 + \frac{15}{34}c & a\frac{15}{34} + \frac{15}{34}\frac{25}{34} \\ c & c\frac{15}{34} + (\frac{25}{34})^2 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} a & \frac{15}{34} \\ c & \frac{25}{34} \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

Comparing the corresponding elements, we have:
\begin{align*} a^2 + \frac{15}{34}c &= a \quad \text{(1)} \\
a\frac{15}{34} + \frac{15}{34}\frac{25}{34} &= \frac{15}{34} \quad \text{(2)} \\
c &= c \quad \text{(3)} \\
c\frac{15}{34} + (\frac{25}{34})^2 &= \frac{25}{34} \quad \text{(4)}\end{align*}

From equation (2), we can solve for $a$:
\begin{align*}
a\frac{15}{34} + \frac{15}{34}\frac{25}{34} &= \frac{15}{34} \\
a\frac{15}{34} &= \frac{15}{34} - \frac{15}{34}\frac{25}{34} \\
a &= 1 - \frac{25}{34} \\
a &= \frac{9}{34}
\end{align*}

From equation (4), we can solve for $c$:
\begin{align*}
c\frac{15}{34} + (\frac{25}{34})^2 &= \frac{25}{34} \\
c\frac{15}{34} &= \frac{25}{34} - (\frac{25}{34})^2 \\
c &= \frac{25}{34} - \frac{25}{34}\frac{25}{34} \\
c &= \frac{25}{34} - \frac{625}{1156} \\
c &= \frac{25 \times 34}{1156} - \frac{625}{1156} \\
c &= \frac{850 - 625}{1156} \\
c &= \frac{225}{1156} \\
c &= \frac{225}{1156}
\end{align*}

Thus, the ordered pair $(a, c)$ is $(\frac{9}{34}, \frac{225}{1156})$.

